canonical:
  title: 祝上疏
  author: 釋無畏
  language: lzh
  text: 慈悲無㝵奚遅拔與之私歲序云徂更切遐長之祝弟子本無三力固昧一心幸作宿緣而濫作師賓居常內省而迴慚佛祖蝗蠹桂玉者足三載何止人譏馬牛襟裾而惑一時恐遭天譴今者乘輿久留於中國時節方當於大寒別開一日之熏勤庶格十方之照了伏願主上殿下乾坤之祥荐至年月之厄都消佛力法力賢聖力以同扶一身無惱皇恩后恩儲副恩之獨厚千載不衰嘉與椒圍而速還坐看桑域之復興
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 祝上疏
  author: 釋無畏
  language: lzh
  text: 慈悲無㝵。奚遅拔與之私。歲序云徂。更切遐長之祝。弟子本無三力。固昧一心。幸作宿緣。而濫作師賓。居常內省而迴慚佛祖。蝗蠹桂玉者足三載。何止人譏。馬牛襟裾而惑一時。恐遭天譴。今者乘輿久留於中國。時節方當於大寒。別開一日之熏勤。庶格十方之照了。伏願主上殿下。乾坤之祥荐至。年月之厄都消。佛力法力賢聖力以同扶。一身無惱。皇恩后恩儲副恩之獨厚。千載不衰。嘉與椒圍而速還。坐看桑域之復興。
korean:
  title: 축원하는 상소
  author: 석무외
  language: kor
  text: 부처님의 자비는 걸림이 없으니 어찌 발여(拔與)하는 사정을 늦추겠습니까만, 세월이 바뀌어 다시 오랜 수명을 축원하기 간절하옵니다. 제자는 본래 세 가지 힘이 없고 한 마음이 어두우나, 다행히 묵은 인연이 있어 외람되게 사빈(師賓)의 지위를 차지하매 항상 마음으로 반성하여 불조(佛祖)에 부끄러워하며, 계옥(桂玉)을 좀먹은 지 3년이 차므로 사람들의 조롱이 그치지 않고, 마우(馬牛)의 옷깃으로 한 때를 의혹시켜 하늘의 벌을 받을까 두려워하옵는데, 이제 승여(乘輿)가 오랫동안 중국에 머무르고 시절이 바야흐로 대한(大寒)에 부딪쳤으므로, 특히 하루의 훈근(熏勤)을 개설하여 혹시 시방의 밝게 비추심을 바라옵니다.원하건대, 주상 전하께 하늘과 땅의 상서가 거듭 이르고 해와 달의 액운이 모두 사라져서, 부처님의 힘과 법의 힘과 성현의 힘이 함께 도와 일신에 괴로움이 없고, 황제의 은혜와 황후의 은혜와 황태자의 은혜가 유달리 두터워 천년토록 줄지 않으며, 반가히 초위(椒圍)와 함께 빨리 돌아와서 승역(乘域)의 부흥을 앉아 보게 하옵소서.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1140_010_0170&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Prayer for the Return
  author: Seok Muwae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Buddha's compassion knows no obstruction, yet I humbly petition for the swift fulfillment of rescue and deliverance. As the seasons turn and years advance, I offer fervent prayers for longevity and blessing.

    I, your disciple, possess none of the three powers and remain benighted in singular understanding. Yet by fortune of ancient karmic bonds, I have undeservedly assumed this position between teacher and guest. In constant self-reflection, I bow in shame before the Buddha and the Patriarchs. For three years now has decay gnawed at the precious jade, and the ridicule of men shows no end. Like an ox in borrowed vestments causing bewilderment, I fear the punishment of Heaven descends upon me.

    Now the imperial retinue lingers long in the Middle Kingdom as the season turns to deep winter's cold. On this day, I kindle special devotion, hoping to illuminate all corners with the Buddha's radiant compassion.

    I humbly beseech: May auspicious signs from Heaven and Earth arrive in succession to the throne. May all calamities of years and months dissolve completely. May the power of Buddha, the power of Dharma, and the power of the worthy saints unite in support, bringing freedom from suffering to the realm.

    May the Emperor's grace, the Empress's grace, and the Crown Prince's grace remain uniquely abundant and endure a thousand ages undiminished. May we all return with gladness, to witness from our seats the restoration of the empire's renewal.
  footnotes:
    - 'The three powers (三力) refer to Buddhist concepts of spiritual capacity: the power of Buddha, the power of Dharma (teaching), and the power of one''s own practice.'
    - The imagery of decay gnawing at precious jade and an ox in borrowed vestments are metaphors for the author's sense of unworthiness and the absurdity of his position, expressing characteristic Buddhist humility.
    - The poem appears to be a petition on behalf of an imperial delegation's return from China, incorporating both Buddhist devotional language and courtly ceremony.
